  "answer": "### Dealing with an Unreliable Friend\n\nBoth *Maxims I* (an Old English gnomic poem) and *Ślokāntara* (a medieval Kawi wisdom anthology) offer distilled counsel on unreliable companions, emphasizing discernment over blind loyalty. In *Maxims I*, betrayal by friends brings wretchedness, and the friendless turn to treacherous substitutes like wolves—urging vigilance in maintaining bonds but warning of their fragility.[^1] The poem laments: \"Blessed is he who thrives in his homeland, wretched is he whom his friends betray,\" and later evokes the peril of isolation: \"A man should hold a friend well on every road... The friendless, unhappy man takes wolves for his companions, a very treacherous beast.\"[^2]\n\n*Ślokāntara* delivers a sharper, more pragmatic maxim in śloka 51: \"Even a stranger, if helpful, is a kinsman; even a kinsman, if harmful, is a stranger. A disease born of the body is harmful; a forest herb that helps is a friend.\"[^3] Here, utility trumps kinship—harmful intimates are discarded like bodily ills, while beneficial outsiders are embraced as true allies (exemplified by figures like Sugrīva preferring strangers Rāma and Lakṣmaṇa over treacherous kin Bāli).\n\n**Ślokāntara*'s counsel travels better across cultures and eras.** Its relational calculus—judge by actions, not blood or proximity—is timelessly actionable, sidestepping the Anglo-Saxon fatalism of inevitable strife or wolfish substitutes. *Maxims I* poignantly evokes emotional ruin but offers less prescriptive strategy, rooted in a heroic ethos of enduring bonds amid wyrd (fate). The Kawi verse, by contrast, equips one to pivot nimbly, aligning with pragmatic Indic traditions of discerning *guna* (qualities) over sentiment.\n\n[^1]: Unknown, *Old English Elegies*, Maxims I [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/06-maxims-i/translation/#p-84cf09).\n\n[^2]: Unknown, *Old English Elegies*, Maxims I [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/06-maxims-i/translation/#p-84cf09).\n\n[^3]: Unknown, *Slokantara*, Chapter 1 [paragraph](/works/unknown-slokantara-d7a628/01/translation/#p-bf093b).",
